Stack

Purpose:
- Current stack memory for runtime, storage, tests, deployment, and static companion assets.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify against source manifests, imports, scripts, and tests before relying on it.
Memory scope: language/runtime stack, dependency policy, storage backend status, and deploy packaging.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: update this file when runtime, storage, dependency, test, or deployment stack changes.
Source of truth: Python imports, `app.py`, `memoryendpoints/`, `tests/`, `scripts/`, and package reports.
Next action for agents: verify stack assumptions from files before adding dependencies, adapters, or deployment claims.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, local credential paths, or private runtime stores.

Current stack:
- Python standard library WSGI runtime.
- No third-party package is bundled as an application runtime dependency; production MySQL/MariaDB uses the hosting environment's database driver.
- HTML, CSS, and browser JavaScript for public pages and static companion site assets.
- Stdlib SQLite relational storage is the unconfigured local default and is live for implemented MATM workflows.
- MySQL/MariaDB relational storage is the verified production backend, selected by protected host configuration and a host-provided driver.
- The legacy file store remains explicit-only compatibility infrastructure and is not the durable tenant knowledge source of truth.
- UAI-1, MCP, A2A, DIDs, verifiable credentials, semantic glyphs, and product-specific adapters are not bundled MemoryEndpoints runtime dependencies. They remain external standards, companion layers, or proposed integrations until an approved implementation adds code and tests.
- LocalEndpoints.com, Carcinus.org, NeuralWikis.com, and UAIX.org are separately governed external product or standards surfaces; MemoryEndpoints integration does not silently inherit their execution, identity, authorization, storage, or release contracts.
- MemoryEndpoints has no bundled arbitrary-code, shell, container, microVM, WebAssembly, V8, eBPF, or MCP-tool execution runtime. Firecracker, gVisor, WebAssembly, hardened containers, and hosted sandboxes are external design candidates until a separately approved runtime adds code, ownership, tests, and deployment evidence.
- OpenAPI and RFC 9457 are the current HTTP description and problem-detail foundations used for design review. RFC robots rules are crawl preferences, `llms.txt` is an optional community proposal, AI Manifest remains draft work, and MCP integration remains subject to service authentication, authorization, consent, and least privilege.
- Packaging excludes `.uai`, raw handoff buckets, prompt drafts, local runtime state, databases, logs, and credential material.
